ganizations, and is now fully integrated into human rights initiatives and international organizations. Those who today call themselves indigenous peoples share significant similarities in their colonial and postcolonial experiences, such as loss of land and subsistence, abrogation of treaties, and the imposition of psychologically and socially destructive assimilation policies. Niezen shows how, from a new position of legitimacy and influence, they are striving for greater recognition of collective rights, in particular their rights to self-determination in international law. These efforts are influencing local politics in turn and encouraging more ambitious goals of autonomy in indigenous communities worldwide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEthnicityxPolitical aspects. 0aHuman rights. 0aIndigenous peoplesxCivil rights. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEthnic identity. 0aIndigenous peoplesxPolitics and government. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  a20th century.  acollective rights.  acultural issues.  aeconomic development.  aglobalism.  ahistorical perspective.  ahistory of indigenism.  ahuman rights.  aidentity.  aindigenism.  aindigenous communities.  aindigenous peoples.  ainternational indigenism.  ainternational labor organization.  ainternational movements.  ainternational organizations.  anonfiction.  anongovernmental organizations.  apolitical activists.  apolitical issues.  apolitical perspective.  asense of self.  asocial activism.  asocial reform.  auniversal rights.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023554040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093669040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520936690423Coveruhttps://www.d